<section id="fb1">
  <p align="left">
    <font face="verdana" size="13" color="#000000">1. 'The first stage takes place at the foundry.'</font>
  </p>
</section>

<section id="fb2">
  <p align="left">
    <font face="verdana" size="13" color="#000000">2. 'The metal is subsequently flattened...in the rolling mill.'</font>
  </p>
</section>

<section id="fb3">
  <p align="left">
    <font face="verdana" size="13" color="#000000">3. 'This sheet metal is then fed into the blanking press.'</font>
  </p>
</section>

<section id="fb4">
  <p align="left">
    <font face="verdana" size="13" color="#000000">4. 'Prior to this (being stamped with a design) they must be softened and cleaned in the annealing and pickling plant.'</font>
  </p>
</section>

<section id="fb5">
  <p align="left">
    <font face="verdana" size="13" color="#000000">5. 'Once this (softening and cleaning) is completed, the blanks go to the coining press.'</font>
  </p>
</section>

<section id="fb6">
  <p align="left">
    <font face="verdana" size="13" color="#000000">6. 'Next, (after being stamped in the coining press) a sample goes through...the Trial of the Pyx.'</font>
  </p>
</section>

<section id="fb7">
  <p align="left">
    <font face="verdana" size="13" color="#000000">7. 'The coins are finally ready for circulation.'</font>
  </p>
</section>

<section id="rt2001">
  <p align="left">
    <font face="verdana" size="13" color="#000000">The words and phrases that we can use to indicate consecutive and concurrent stages in a process are often called 'sequence makers'. They help the reader understand the chronological order of a process and you should use them in reports that describe flow charts.</font>
  </p>
